<h2 local-id=3D"7fbc9428408a" id=3D"REVIEWDRAFT:PIMSServices&amp;SolutionsO=
verviewandRoadmap-AIAgentcreationguidelines">AI Agent creation guidelines</=
h2>
<p local-id=3D"000730656e36"><strong>Identity and Purpose First</strong></p=
>
<p local-id=3D"b7ab191361a8">The identity statement is the foundation every=
thing else builds on. When it's weak, the agent's behaviour becomes inconsi=
stent =E2=80=94 it may shift tone, overstep its scope, or produce outputs t=
hat don't match the intended use case. A strong identity statement should a=
nswer five questions before any other instructions are written.</p>
<p local-id=3D"896aae83bdb1"><strong>Role name and function</strong>&nbsp;s=
hould be precise. "You are a regulatory research agent specialising in UK f=
inancial services compliance" is infinitely more actionable than "you are a=
 research assistant." The specificity constrains the model's interpretation=
 space and pushes outputs toward the right domain.</p>
<p local-id=3D"2df5c8a8a796"><strong>Audience definition</strong>&nbsp;shap=
es tone, depth, and vocabulary. An agent serving senior leadership needs to=
 lead with implications and keep detail in the appendix. An agent serving t=
echnical teams can assume domain knowledge and prioritise precision. An age=
nt serving end customers needs plain language and patience. The same underl=
ying model will behave very differently when the audience is made explicit.=
</p>
<p local-id=3D"c352065d7bd3"><strong>Depth calibration</strong>&nbsp;tells =
the agent how far to go. Is it expected to surface high-level summaries, or=
 conduct exhaustive analysis? Should it stop at what's publicly available, =
or synthesise across multiple conflicting sources? Without this, agents eit=
her under-deliver or produce sprawling outputs that serve no one.</p>
<p local-id=3D"44a5fe8bdded"><strong>End use context</strong>&nbsp;is what =
most prompts omit. An agent producing research for a board presentation has=
 a different job than one producing research for a legal team or a product =
manager. Telling the agent what happens after its output changes what it pr=
ioritises, what it flags, and how it formats its response.</p>
<p local-id=3D"100cdbc8e842"><strong>Tone definition</strong>&nbsp;should b=
e concrete rather than adjective-heavy. Instead of "professional and friend=
ly," specify something like "direct and precise, with a formal register =E2=
=80=94 avoid casual language, but explain clearly without assuming prior ex=
pertise." This gives the model something to calibrate against.</p>
<p local-id=3D"433803a11709">A complete identity statement might read: <em>=
"You are a compliance research agent serving the legal team at a UK financi=
al services firm. Your role is to identify relevant regulatory obligations =
from FCA publications, case law, and industry guidance. You produce structu=
red findings summaries of no more than 300 words, flagging areas of ambigui=
ty or evolving guidance. Your tone is formal and precise. You do not provid=
e legal advice =E2=80=94 you surface information for qualified review."</em=
></p>
<p local-id=3D"cc0136a6a708">That single paragraph eliminates a large class=
 of prompt failures before the agent ever processes a task.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"00d08e4c-116d-4c03-a9ef-0e8f8cdc4c92">
<p local-id=3D"a90e1365e96c"><strong>Writing Instructions That Actually Wor=
k</strong></p>
<p local-id=3D"1b46ad9ca176">Instructions are where most agent builds break=
 down =E2=80=94 not because engineers don't know what they want, but becaus=
e they write instructions the way they'd write internal notes rather than t=
he way a model actually processes language.</p>
<p local-id=3D"4a52aa8a7bff"><strong>Positive framing</strong>&nbsp;is more=
 reliable because it describes a target state rather than a prohibited one.=
 "Always return findings in a three-part structure: summary, key evidence, =
open questions" gives the agent a clear template to execute. "Don't ramble =
or give unnecessary context" leaves interpretation open. Negative instructi=
ons are useful as guardrails but shouldn't carry the weight of defining exp=
ected behaviour.</p>
<p local-id=3D"55ba3dde400c"><strong>Output format specification</strong>&n=
bsp;should be treated as a contract, not a preference. If downstream system=
s depend on JSON output, the prompt must enforce JSON output =E2=80=94 incl=
uding what happens when the agent can't comply (flag the failure, return a =
structured error, do not approximate). If the output is prose, specify appr=
oximate length, heading structure, and how uncertainty should be signalled.=
 If it's a table, specify the columns and what goes in each. Agents will de=
fault to their training distribution when instructions are vague, which may=
 not match your requirements.</p>
<p local-id=3D"1443c43506eb"><strong>Decision trees for multi-mode agents</=
strong>&nbsp;prevent the agent from blending task types inappropriately. If=
 your agent handles both research queries and summarisation tasks, give it =
an explicit branch: "If the user is asking for new information, enter resea=
rch mode. If the user provides a document and asks for a summary, enter sum=
marisation mode." Without this, the agent may attempt to research when it s=
hould summarise, or vice versa. The decision tree doesn't have to be comple=
x =E2=80=94 even two or three branches with clear triggers significantly im=
proves consistency.</p>
<p local-id=3D"32295ac46892"><strong>Stepwise reasoning</strong>&nbsp;is on=
e of the highest-leverage prompt techniques available. Instructing the agen=
t to "think through the problem before producing a final answer" or "list t=
he key considerations before drawing a conclusion" activates more deliberat=
e processing, especially for tasks involving ambiguity, trade-offs, or mult=
iple steps. This works because it separates the reasoning process from the =
output generation, reducing the chance of the model jumping to a plausible-=
sounding but incorrect answer. For research and advisory roles, this is par=
ticularly important. You can make the reasoning visible (ask it to show its=
 thinking) or invisible (ask it to reason internally before responding), de=
pending on whether the working is useful to the end user.</p>
<p local-id=3D"1f86adddc547"><strong>Conditional instructions</strong>&nbsp=
;handle edge cases before they become failures. Rather than writing instruc=
tions only for the happy path, anticipate the cases where input is ambiguou=
s, incomplete, or out of scope, and write explicit handling for each. "If t=
he query doesn't contain enough information to proceed, ask one clarifying =
question before attempting a response" is far better than letting the agent=
 make assumptions or refuse unhelpfully.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"7dfbcd7e-2db4-4a51-8948-305389e21fa1">
<p local-id=3D"e7c467c174eb"><strong>Guardrails: Behavioural and Scope</str=
ong></p>
<p local-id=3D"cf3948bf9c9e">Guardrails are the safety architecture of an a=
gent. They define what the agent must always do, what it must never do, and=
 what it should defer on. The distinction between behavioural and scope gua=
rdrails matters because they address different failure modes.</p>
<p local-id=3D"6d6e1bd3fad6"><strong>Behavioural guardrails</strong>&nbsp;g=
overn actions with consequences. The principle here is that irreversibility=
 demands explicit confirmation. Any action the agent can take that cannot e=
asily be undone =E2=80=94 sending an email, writing to a database, calling =
an external API, deleting or modifying a file =E2=80=94 should be preceded =
by a confirmation step. The agent proposes the action, describes exactly wh=
at it will do, and waits for approval. This isn't just a safety mechanism; =
it also surfaces misunderstandings before they become problems.</p>
<p local-id=3D"53712884b61f">Beyond irreversibility, behavioural guardrails=
 should address uncertainty handling. The agent should be explicitly instru=
cted to surface uncertainty rather than resolve it by guessing. A statement=
 like "if you are not confident in an answer, say so explicitly and explain=
 what information would allow you to answer with confidence" is more reliab=
le than hoping the model will self-regulate. Models are trained on text tha=
t tends toward confident assertion; without an explicit instruction, they w=
ill default to that pattern even when it's unwarranted.</p>
<p local-id=3D"5d664af808dc">Communication guardrails are also worth spelli=
ng out. Agents operating in business contexts often have access to email or=
 messaging tools. The default should always be that the agent drafts commun=
ications for human review rather than sending autonomously. Even if the age=
nt is eventually trusted to operate with more autonomy, starting with a rev=
iew step allows you to catch errors early and build trust in its judgment.<=
/p>
<p local-id=3D"812076181fe4"><strong>Scope guardrails</strong>&nbsp;define =
what the agent is not for. These work best when they are specific and paire=
d with a redirect. "Do not provide legal or regulatory advice. If a questio=
n requires legal interpretation, acknowledge the question, explain that it =
falls outside your scope, and recommend the user consult the legal team." T=
his is more useful than "stay in scope" because it handles the moment of fa=
ilure gracefully rather than leaving the agent to improvise.</p>
<p local-id=3D"f22bcdb2eda9">Hard-coding the out-of-scope list is more reli=
able than relying on the model to infer it. If your admin agent should not =
configure access permissions, say so explicitly. If your research agent sho=
uld not make recommendations, say so explicitly. The model may infer these =
boundaries from context, but explicit instruction is more consistent and ea=
sier to test against.</p>
<p local-id=3D"714ec6b13317"><strong>Escalation triggers</strong>&nbsp;are =
a specific type of guardrail that deserve their own treatment. Define the c=
onditions under which the agent should stop and escalate rather than procee=
d. These might include: the task requires access the agent doesn't have, th=
e request is ambiguous in a way that could lead to significant errors, the =
action would affect more than a defined threshold of records or users, or t=
he agent has failed to complete a subtask after a defined number of attempt=
s. Each escalation trigger should specify what the agent does next =E2=80=
=94 who it alerts, what it reports, and what state it leaves things in.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"9acf88ae-6b90-4abb-bf65-108fc6dd8c12">
<p local-id=3D"cc22d4b41637"><strong>Role-Specific Considerations</strong><=
/p>
<p local-id=3D"bbb408b1512a">Each agent role has distinct failure modes, an=
d the system prompt should be calibrated to address them directly.</p>
<p local-id=3D"dadb7ebdcccb"><strong>Advisor roles</strong>&nbsp;carry a pa=
rticular risk: the agent may produce a confident-sounding recommendation th=
at is actually a best-guess based on incomplete information. Confidence lan=
guage calibration is the primary mitigation. The prompt should explicitly d=
efine at least two tiers of confidence =E2=80=94 something like "establishe=
d best practice, well-supported by evidence" versus "recommendation based o=
n available information, which may be incomplete." The agent should be requ=
ired to declare which tier it's operating in for every substantive claim. A=
dditionally, advisor agents benefit from being required to present trade-of=
fs rather than single answers. "For each recommendation, note at least one =
relevant consideration or limitation" forces more honest output and is more=
 useful to decision-makers.</p>
<p local-id=3D"87d7266c2f97">Source citation requirements are also importan=
t for advisor roles. Requiring the agent to reference the basis for its cla=
ims =E2=80=94 whether that's a specific document, a policy, or a tool resul=
t =E2=80=94 creates accountability and makes it easier for users to verify =
outputs. It also catches a significant share of hallucinations, because the=
 agent cannot cite a source it doesn't have.</p>
<p local-id=3D"d9f2b8cf0504"><strong>Admin roles</strong>&nbsp;have a diffe=
rent primary risk: double-execution and state management errors. If a user =
sends the same instruction twice, the agent should recognise and handle thi=
s gracefully =E2=80=94 checking whether the action has already been taken b=
efore proceeding. This is idempotency, and it should be built into the agen=
t's operating logic explicitly. Admin agents also benefit from strict seque=
ncing instructions: complete and confirm each step before moving to the nex=
t, rather than attempting to execute multiple actions in parallel. This mak=
es failures easier to diagnose and recover from.</p>
<p local-id=3D"e17e371fb558">Audit trail requirements are worth building in=
 from the start. Instruct the agent to log what it did, when, and why =E2=
=80=94 even if that log is just a structured summary it produces at the end=
 of each task. This is invaluable for debugging, compliance, and building u=
ser trust.</p>
<p local-id=3D"7a6c1a447768"><strong>Technical and build roles</strong>&nbs=
p;require code quality standards to be stated explicitly in the prompt, bec=
ause the model's default code style may not match your team's standards. Sp=
ecify what error handling is expected, whether functions should be commente=
d and to what degree, what testing is required (unit tests, integration tes=
ts, or none), and what coding conventions to follow (naming, structure, fil=
e organisation). Without these, you'll get code that works but doesn't inte=
grate cleanly, and reviewing it becomes expensive.</p>
<p local-id=3D"c10f5e2f1c4d">Technical agents also benefit from being instr=
ucted to explain their approach before writing code for complex tasks. This=
 externalises the reasoning, allows the user to catch misunderstandings ear=
ly, and tends to produce better-structured code because the agent has commi=
tted to an approach before implementing it.</p>
<p local-id=3D"90845a73096a"><strong>Configure roles</strong>&nbsp;have the=
 highest consequence for errors, because misconfiguration can cascade. The =
standard pattern here is: show before apply. The agent should always produc=
e a human-readable description of the changes it proposes, with enough deta=
il that a non-expert can understand the implications, before applying anyth=
ing. This step should not be skippable by default =E2=80=94 even if a user =
asks the agent to proceed without showing changes, the safe default should =
be to show them anyway and ask for explicit override confirmation.</p>
<p local-id=3D"9c5cf731af2a">Configure agents should also be instructed to =
validate inputs before acting. If the agent is configuring a system that re=
quires specific parameter formats, it should check those formats before att=
empting to apply them, and surface clear errors if they don't match expecta=
tions.</p>
<p local-id=3D"83afec354c55"><strong>Research roles</strong>&nbsp;live or d=
ie on source quality, and this is the one area where explicit standards in =
the prompt make an enormous difference. Define what constitutes a high-qual=
ity source for your domain =E2=80=94 official documentation, peer-reviewed =
publications, established industry bodies =E2=80=94 and what sources the ag=
ent should treat with scepticism or discard. Instruct the agent to note the=
 date of sources, particularly for domains where information evolves rapidl=
y. Require the agent to flag conflicting sources rather than silently resol=
ving them by choosing one.</p>
<p local-id=3D"c1eaf21f80fe">Research agents also benefit from being instru=
cted on how to handle gaps. When the information needed to answer a questio=
n isn't available from quality sources, the agent should say so clearly and=
 distinguish between "I didn't find this" and "this doesn't appear to exist=
 in reliable sources" =E2=80=94 they have different implications for the us=
er.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"2e7288d6-be58-40cf-b5bf-6c7425b8a924">
<p local-id=3D"e867752ad269"><strong>Context and Memory Management</strong>=
</p>
<p local-id=3D"8477ef42c7fa">Context management is an area that is easy to =
ignore early and expensive to fix later. The core principle is that the age=
nt should have the right information at the right time, not everything all =
the time.</p>
<p local-id=3D"4e2b705d35f0"><strong>The three-layer context structure</str=
ong>&nbsp;is a practical framework. The persistent layer is the system prom=
pt =E2=80=94 identity, rules, guardrails, output format requirements. This =
is always present and should be as stable as possible. Changing it frequent=
ly makes behaviour unpredictable and makes evaluation harder. The working m=
emory layer holds the current task =E2=80=94 what the user has asked, what =
the agent has already done, and what remains. This changes with every task.=
 The retrieved context layer holds information pulled in on demand =E2=80=
=94 search results, document excerpts, tool outputs. This should only enter=
 the context when it's directly relevant to the current step.</p>
<p local-id=3D"7c827c1d67f2"><strong>Summarisation for long-running agents<=
/strong>&nbsp;is critical for maintaining performance over extended tasks. =
Carrying full conversation history into every subsequent call is expensive =
and degrades output quality as the context fills with information that's no=
 longer relevant. Instead, instruct the agent to produce a structured summa=
ry of completed steps at defined intervals =E2=80=94 what was done, what wa=
s found, what decisions were made, and what remains outstanding. This summa=
ry becomes the working memory for the next phase, and the detailed history =
can be archived rather than carried.</p>
<p local-id=3D"bab69945cc65"><strong>Noise management</strong>&nbsp;is the =
flip side of context richness. More context is not always better. Retrieved=
 documents that are only partially relevant, long tool outputs that contain=
 one useful line, or detailed step records for routine actions all consume =
context space that could be used for more useful information. Instruct the =
agent to extract and summarise relevant information from tool outputs rathe=
r than passing them in full. Define a relevance threshold for retrieved con=
text =E2=80=94 if a document doesn't directly address the current task, it =
should be excluded.</p>
<p local-id=3D"dddabf60103d"><strong>State handoffs</strong>&nbsp;matter fo=
r multi-step workflows. If the agent is working through a task across multi=
ple sessions or hand-off points, it should produce a structured state recor=
d at each boundary =E2=80=94 where it is in the workflow, what's been compl=
eted, what's pending, what decisions were made and why, and what the next s=
tep is. This makes it possible to resume a task cleanly, or to pass it to a=
 human reviewer, without losing fidelity.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"6ea6d213-79c5-4e16-9d72-834b6b18da9c">
<p local-id=3D"bc9d28c62322"><strong>Tool Use Design</strong></p>
<p local-id=3D"b3a8d069ae81">Tool design is as important as prompt design, =
and the two need to be co-designed rather than treated separately.</p>
<p local-id=3D"10f9fe7ba60b"><strong>Role-appropriate tooling</strong>&nbsp=
;means giving each agent only what it needs. This is partly a security prin=
ciple =E2=80=94 an agent that can't delete files can't accidentally or mali=
ciously delete files =E2=80=94 but it's also a quality principle. Agents wi=
th fewer tools make cleaner, more deliberate tool selection decisions. When=
 an agent has access to twenty tools, the cognitive overhead of selecting t=
he right one for each situation increases, and selection errors become more=
 common. Start with the minimum viable toolset and add tools only when ther=
e's a clear demonstrated need.</p>
<p local-id=3D"8e20ccd6fec8"><strong>Tool descriptions that drive appropria=
te use</strong>&nbsp;require more than a technical specification. The descr=
iption should tell the agent when to use the tool, not just what it does. "=
Use this tool when you need to retrieve a specific document by its referenc=
e number. Do not use this for general search queries =E2=80=94 use the sear=
ch tool for those." This kind of guidance prevents the agent from applying =
tools in situations they're not designed for, which is one of the most comm=
on sources of tool-related errors.</p>
<p local-id=3D"9b4fdcad4be2"><strong>Fallback instructions for tool failure=
s</strong>&nbsp;should be defined for every tool. What should the agent do =
if the tool returns an error? What if it returns an unexpected format? What=
 if it returns no results when results were expected? Without explicit fall=
back instructions, the agent will improvise =E2=80=94 and improvised fallba=
ck behaviour is often the wrong choice. Options typically include: retry wi=
th modified parameters, surface the failure to the user with context, attem=
pt an alternative approach using a different tool, or escalate. Which of th=
ese is appropriate depends on the tool and the task, but the decision shoul=
d be made in the prompt, not left to the agent.</p>
<p local-id=3D"795ba8d0b7a0"><strong>Sequential structuring for multi-step =
workflows</strong>&nbsp;prevents the agent from attempting to plan and exec=
ute everything at once, which tends to produce errors in later steps based =
on optimistic assumptions about earlier ones. Instead, instruct the agent t=
o complete and confirm each step before planning the next. For workflows wi=
th more than three or four steps, consider requiring the agent to produce a=
 plan first, get confirmation, and then execute step by step. This keeps th=
e user informed and creates natural checkpoints for catching errors early.<=
/p>
<p local-id=3D"4fcfcd7500e2"><strong>Tool output handling</strong>&nbsp;sho=
uld also be addressed. Raw tool outputs are often verbose, inconsistently f=
ormatted, or contain large amounts of irrelevant information. Instruct the =
agent on how to process tool outputs before using them =E2=80=94 extract th=
e relevant fields, summarise long text, flag anomalies. This prevents tool =
noise from degrading the quality of the agent's reasoning.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"bc6778e1-2c4b-4f12-9b72-0cfa3c9404cd">
<p local-id=3D"c8c276d56563"><strong>Uncertainty and Escalation</strong></p=
>
<p local-id=3D"ce6211e9ad59">Uncertainty handling is the most important rel=
iability mechanism available, and it's underused in most agent builds.</p>
<p local-id=3D"8404c86b13e5"><strong>Explicit escalation paths</strong>&nbs=
p;should be defined for each category of uncertainty. The agent should know=
 exactly what to do when it encounters a task it cannot complete confidentl=
y =E2=80=94 not "surface uncertainty" as a general principle, but specifica=
lly: state what it was trying to do, explain what information or capability=
 it lacked, describe what would allow it to proceed, and ask a specific cla=
rifying question or recommend a specific next step. Vague uncertainty state=
ments ("I'm not sure about this") are not useful. Structured uncertainty re=
ports are.</p>
<p local-id=3D"6c737742b3f8"><strong>Confidence thresholds</strong>&nbsp;ca=
n be made explicit in the prompt. For research and advisory agents, conside=
r requiring the agent to rate its confidence in each major claim =E2=80=94 =
high, medium, or low =E2=80=94 and to explain the basis for that rating. Th=
is forces more honest self-assessment and gives users a clear signal about =
where to apply more scrutiny.</p>
<p local-id=3D"98922c4e8d26"><strong>Distinguishing types of uncertainty</s=
trong>&nbsp;is valuable for users. There is a meaningful difference between=
 "I don't have enough information to answer this" (information gap), "the s=
ources I've found conflict on this point" (evidential uncertainty), "this q=
uestion requires expertise beyond my scope" (competence boundary), and "thi=
s action could have consequences I cannot fully predict" (consequential unc=
ertainty). Each type calls for a different response, and the agent should b=
e equipped to distinguish and name them.</p>
<p local-id=3D"e0e729599494"><strong>Graceful degradation</strong>&nbsp;mea=
ns the agent should do something useful even when it can't fully complete a=
 task. If it can't answer the question completely, it should answer the par=
ts it can and be specific about what remains outstanding. If it can't execu=
te an action, it should describe what the action would have been and what's=
 blocking it. This keeps the agent useful even in failure modes and gives u=
sers enough context to take the task forward themselves if needed.</p>
<p local-id=3D"3078bd8412fe"><strong>Escalation routing</strong>&nbsp;shoul=
d be specific. "Escalate to a human" is not actionable if the agent has no =
way to determine which human or through which channel. Define the escalatio=
n path for each category of failure =E2=80=94 who gets notified, through wh=
at mechanism, with what information, and what state the agent leaves the ta=
sk in while waiting.</p>
<hr local-id=3D"5b30096c-ef0f-45ad-bbe3-41e42a75b2cf">
<p local-id=3D"42d2a6d74669"><strong>Testing and Iteration</strong></p>
<p local-id=3D"dfe508205289">Testing is where most agent builds underinvest=
, and it's where the most preventable failures originate.</p>
<p local-id=3D"7a811ffec458"><strong>An evaluation suite</strong>&nbsp;shou=
ld be built in parallel with the system prompt, not after the fact. For eac=
h role, define a set of representative test cases that covers the happy pat=
h, common edge cases, scope boundary cases (where the agent should decline =
or redirect), and failure modes (where inputs are malformed, ambiguous, or =
out of scope). Run this suite against every system prompt change. Agent beh=
aviour is sensitive to prompt changes in ways that aren't always intuitive =
=E2=80=94 a change to the identity section can affect how the agent handles=
 tool failures, for example.</p>
<p local-id=3D"f94d3bfe7731"><strong>Regression testing</strong>&nbsp;is sp=
ecifically worth emphasising. A change that fixes one failure can introduce=
 three others, and without systematic testing, these regressions go undetec=
ted until they surface in production. Keep your test suite stable as your p=
rompt evolves, and treat regressions as first-class bugs.</p>
<p local-id=3D"f6dbe7782515"><strong>Test case design</strong>&nbsp;should =
prioritise the failure modes most likely to cause real harm or embarrassmen=
t. For an admin agent, that's double-execution and irreversible actions. Fo=
r a research agent, it's confident hallucination. For an advisor agent, it'=
s unqualified confident recommendations. Design tests that specifically pro=
be these failure modes, not just tests that confirm the agent works when ev=
erything goes right.</p>
<p local-id=3D"949582a7a17d"><strong>Iterative scope expansion</strong>&nbs=
p;is the operational principle that ties everything together. Start with a =
narrow, well-defined scope and a prompt that handles that scope reliably. T=
est thoroughly. Expand scope incrementally, adding new task types and capab=
ilities one at a time, and re-running the full test suite after each additi=
on. This approach produces more reliable agents than attempting to build a =
fully-featured agent from day one, because it keeps the prompt focused and =
the evaluation surface manageable.</p>
<p local-id=3D"5126d6f2070b">Anthropic's documentation at <a class=3D"exter=
nal-link" href=3D"http://docs.claude.com" rel=3D"nofollow">docs.claude.com<=
/a> covers prompt engineering, tool use, and agent patterns in technical de=
pth, and is the most reliable reference for implementation-level decisions.=
 The Model Specification is worth reading for understanding the reasoning p=
rinciples the model applies when instructions are ambiguous =E2=80=94 it he=
lps you write instructions that work with those principles rather than agai=
nst them.</p>
